# Go coding standards

Follow `docs/go_coding_standards.md`, Effective Go, and Go Code Review Comments.

## Readability first

- Prefer straightforward Go over clever tricks.
- Keep functions focused and responsibilities narrow.
- Choose names that match Go conventions and reveal intent.
- Keep exported APIs in `internal/*` minimal and purposeful.

## Error handling

- Check errors explicitly.
- Wrap errors with actionable context using `%w`.
- Do not log-and-return the same error unless there is a clear ownership reason.
- Do not silently swallow errors.

## Package and API design

- Use interfaces at consumption boundaries, not preemptively.
- Avoid broad utility packages that hide ownership.
- Keep constructors explicit about required dependencies.
- Favor immutable inputs and explicit return values where practical.

## Concurrency

- Treat goroutines, channels, locks, and shared state as high-risk areas (this repo uses little concurrency; keep it that way unless justified).
- Document cancellation and ownership when adding background work.
- Prefer `context.Context` on I/O (e.g. `internal/feed`, `internal/input` HTTP fetch).

## Testing

- Prefer table-driven tests when they improve clarity.
- Test behavior and contracts, not implementation trivia.
- Cover edge cases, failure paths, and concurrency-sensitive behavior when present.

## Formatting and lint

- Code must pass `gofmt`, `go vet`, and `golangci-lint` (see `Makefile` and CI).
